        "faq_item_zRHyxG": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Can I use the glazes right away?",
            "text": "<p>That depends a bit.</p><p>Brush glazes can be used immediately after mixing.</p><p>It's best to let immersion glazes rest for at least 24 hours. After this rest period, check two important parameters: the specific gravity and the viscosity. Be sure to consult the instruction booklet and the <a href=\"/pages/instructional-videos\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Instructional Videos\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">instructional videos</span></a> to see how.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_wCV4rY": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What is specific gravity and should I measure it?",
            "text": "<p>The specific gravity of a glaze indicates the amount of water and solids in the glaze. It increases over time due to evaporation of water from the glaze, but also through the glazing process itself. Specific gravity is an important parameter that should always be measured before dipping and pouring. With brush glazes, the specific gravity will remain much more constant and requires less frequent measurement.</p><p><a href=\"https://video.wixstatic.com/video/8d1e89_77137c1841aa48ccab40bb1bb83b203b/1080p/mp4/file.mp4\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Learn how to measure specific gravity here.</span></a> You'll also find this explanation in the instruction booklet.</p><p>Compare the obtained specific gravity with the instructions on the SOGO glaze package. Is it higher? Add water and re-measure until you reach the ideal specific gravity. Be careful not to add too much water! Is the specific gravity lower? Then your glaze contains too much water. Wait until the glaze has settled and carefully remove the water with a syringe. Re-measure the specific gravity until you reach the correct value. Always measure the specific gravity of a dip glaze before a glazing session.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_JFeCV4": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What is the viscosity of a glaze? Should I measure it?",
            "text": "<p>Viscosity is the consistency of the glaze in the bucket or pot. A glaze that is too thin or too thick can alter the glaze color or even cause it to run. Checking the viscosity of brush-applied glazes is less important. The number of brushed layers plays a significant role in achieving the correct color.</p><p>You check the viscosity of glazes before pouring or dipping. This changes over time due to environmental factors such as the temperature in the studio. You measure the viscosity immediately after checking and adjusting the specific gravity.</p><p><a href=\"https://video.wixstatic.com/video/8d1e89_e8810faa254747db8ce434cd366bd435/1080p/mp4/file.mp4\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">You can find out how to measure viscosity here.</span></a> This is also explained in the instruction manual.</p><p>A simple viscosity meter (also called a flow cup) is an indispensable tool for reproducible glaze results. <a href=\"/products/viscositeitsmeter\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Viscositeitsmeter\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">You can purchase one here.</span></a></p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_8gCWcq": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "I use the finger dip method for viscosity. Is that okay?",
            "text": "<p>The <a href=\"https://video.wixstatic.com/video/8d1e89_98dca0af1d4a4bb4ac757350a247f0b0/1080p/mp4/file.mp4\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">finger-dip method</span></a> , where you dip a gloved finger into a glaze to test its thickness, provides an indication of viscosity. However, it's a bit of a guessing game. You need a fair amount of experience. Furthermore, not every SOGO glaze needs to be the same thickness to achieve good results.</p><p>It is best to check the viscosity with a <a href=\"/products/viscositeitsmeter\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Viscositeitsmeter\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">flow cup</span></a> to achieve good results.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_bANMDT": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Do I need to re-sieve my glaze regularly?",
            "text": "<p>Sifting a glaze with a <a href=\"/products/glazuurzeef-60-mesh\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Glazuurzeef 60 mesh\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">glaze sieve</span></a> (minimum 60 mesh) is necessary at the following times:</p><ol><li>After mixing the powder glaze with water or brush.</li><li>If there are a lot of chunks hanging from the edge of the bucket that have fallen into the glaze.</li><li>If grains or small stones appear to be forming in the enamel.</li></ol><p>In this last situation, crystals have formed in the glaze. These crystals are caused by certain components of the glaze, especially after a long period of rest with temperature fluctuations. These small stones are important components of the glaze and should not simply be discarded. After all, you are throwing away important raw materials if you do so.</p><p>After sifting, scrape the sieve clean and add the granules/pebbles to a small jar. Add a little hot water. Stir well, and you'll see them dissolve quickly. Add this back to the glaze. <a href=\"https://video.wixstatic.com/video/8d1e89_77137c1841aa48ccab40bb1bb83b203b/1080p/mp4/file.mp4\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">You may need to re-measure the specific gravity of your glaze</span></a><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\"> .</span></p>"
          }
        },
        "category_VH7X4x": {
