        "faq_item_fnxwaB": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "At what temperature should SOGO glazes be fired?",
            "text": "<p>SOGO glazes are low-temperature stoneware glazes. This means they should be fired in the \"colder\" range of stoneware. Stoneware glazes range from approximately 1200°C to 1300°C. SOGO glazes are best fired between 1200°C and 1230°C in modern, well-insulated kilns.</p><p>However, simply describing a final temperature isn't enough. The firing path, the oven's insulation, and the age of the coils all play a role.</p><p>Instead of temperature I prefer to speak of heat work. This is measured with</p><p>Melting cones (also called cones). SOGO glazes are all designed for melting cone 7. Some can also be fired slightly lower or higher. This is indicated on the packaging.</p><p>I use this simple firing curve to get a melt cone 7 to bend perfectly.</p><p>150°C per hour up to 1050°C</p><p>60°C per hour up to 1215°C</p><p>10 minutes of oscillation (holding the temperature) at 1215°C</p><p>uncontrolled cooling</p><p>Every oven is different. You'll need to use melting cones to check whether your selected program actually reaches melting cone 7.</p><p><a href=\"/products/self-supporting-orton-kegel-7\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Self-supporting Orton kegel 7\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">You can buy cones in the webshop.</span></a> You can also find more information in<a href=\"https://video.wixstatic.com/video/8d1e89_fc30fcd1f86c4a16a6185417c01260f1/1080p/mp4/file.mp4\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\"> this instructional video</span></a> .</p>"
          }
        },
